During the Vietnam war the Americans sprayed 42 million liters of toxic chemicals most of it Agent Orange.
About 19 million gallons of Agent Orange and other chemicals were used to defoliate trees in the jungles of Vietnam beginning in 1962.
The study retains three forms of cancer as chemical acne as linked to use of herbicides to defoliate the Vietnam countryside.
Veterans do not have to prove they were exposed to Agent Orange or other herbicides containing the toxic substance dioxin.
The Vietnamese Red Cross launched a special fund for victims of Agent Orange.

